sentence-detokenized: EU rejects German call to boycott British lamb.
Peter Blackburn
BRUSSELS 1996-08-22
The European Commission said on Thursday it disagreed with German advice to consumers to avoid British lamb until scientists determine whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Germany's representative on the EU veterinary committee, Werner Zwingmann, said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheep meat from countries other than Britain until scientific advice was clearer.
"We do not support such a recommendation because we see no basis for it," the Commission's chief spokesman Nikolaus van der Pas told a press briefing.
He said further scientific study was needed and if it was found that action was needed, it should be taken by the European Union.

He said a proposal made last month by EU Farm Commissioner Franz Fischler to ban sheep brains, spleens and spinal cords from the human and animal food chains was a highly specific and precautionary measure to protect human health.
Fischler proposed EU-wide measures following reports from Britain and France that under laboratory conditions sheep could contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) - mad cow disease.

But Fischler agreed to review his proposal after the EU's standing veterinary committee, mational animal health officials, questioned whether such action was justified because there was only a slight risk to human health.
Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio had earlier accused Fischler, at a meeting of EU agriculture ministers, of causing unjustified alarm through "dangerous generalisation".
Only France and Britain supported Fischler's proposal.
The EU's veterinary and multidisciplinary scientific committees are due to re-examine the issue early next month and make recommendations to senior veterinary officials.
Sheep have long been known to contract scrapie, a BSE-like brain disease believed to have been transferred to cattle through feed containing animal waste.

British farmers denied on Thursday that there was any danger to human health from their sheep, but expressed concern that the German government's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could influence consumers across Europe.
"What we have to be very careful about is how other countries will take the lead from Germany," John Lloyd Jones, president of the Welsh National Farmers' Union (NFU), said on BBC radio.

Bonn led efforts to protect public health after consumer confidence collapsed in March after a British report suggested humans could contract a disease similar to mad cow disease by eating contaminated meat.
Germany imported 47,600 sheep from Britain last year, almost half of total imports.
She brought in 4,275 tonnes of British mutton, about 10 per cent of total imports.
Rare Hendrix draft song sells for almost $17,000.
A rare handwritten draft of a song by American guitar legend Jimi Hendrix sold for almost $17,000 on Thursday at an auction of some of the late musician's favourite belongings.
A Florida restaurant paid £10,925 ($16,935) for the draft of "Ain't no tell", which Hendrix wrote on a London hotel stationery shop in late 1966.
At the end of a concert in January 1967 in the English city of Nottingham, he threw the sheet of paper into the audience, where it was retrieved by a fan.
Buyers also snapped up 16 other items that were put up for auction by Hendrix's former girlfriend Kathy Etchingham, who lived with him from 1966 to 1969.
They included a black lacquer and mother-of-pearl inlaid box used by Hendrix to store his drugs, which an anonymous Australian buyer bought for 5,060 pounds ($7,845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970, aged 27.
China says Taiwan spoils the atmosphere for talks.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
On Thursday, China accused Taipei of spoiling the mood for a resumption of talks across the Taiwan Strait with a visit by Taiwanese Vice President Lien Chan to Ukraine this week that angered Beijing.

Speaking just hours after Chinese state media said the time was right to start political talks with Taiwan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang told Reuters, "The atmosphere necessary for the opening of talks has been disrupted by Taiwanese authorities."
State media quoted China's chief negotiator with Taipei, Tang Shubei, as telling a visiting Taiwanese group on Wednesday that it was time for the rivals to hold political talks.
"Now is the time for the two sides to engage in political talks
which is to end the state of hostility, "Thursday's overseas edition of People's Daily quoted Tang as saying.

Shen from the Foreign Ministry told Reuters Television in an interview that he had read reports of Tang's comments, but gave no details of why the negotiator had deemed the time right for talks with Taiwan, which Beijing considers a renegade province.
China, which has long opposed all Taipei's efforts to gain greater international recognition, was infuriated by a visit to Ukraine this week by Taiwan's Vice President Lien.
China says time has come for Taiwan talks.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China said it was time for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island should take practical steps towards that goal.

Consultations are to be held to set the time and format of the talks, the official Xinhua news agency quoted Tang Shubei, executive vice president of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait, as saying late on Wednesday.
German car registration in July up to 14.2 pct yr / yr.
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
German first-time registrations of motor vehicles jumped 14.2 per cent in July this year compared with the year-earlier period, the federal office for motor vehicles said on Thursday.
The office said 356,725 new cars were registered in July 1996 -- 304,850 passenger cars and 15,613 trucks.
The figures represent a 13.6% increase for passenger cars and a 2.2% decline for trucks from July 1995.
The registration of motorbikes increased 32.7% in the period.
The growth was partly due to an increase in the number of Germans buying German cars abroad, while manufacturers said domestic demand was weak, the federal office said.
Almost all German car manufacturers recorded gains in registration numbers in the period.
Volkswagen AG gained 77,719 registrations, just over a quarter of the total.
Opel AG together with General Motors came second with 49,269 registrations, 16.4% of the total value.
Third was Ford with 35,563 registrations, or 11.7%.
Only Seat and Porsche had fewer registrations in July 1996 compared to July last year.
The headquarters recorded 3,420 registrations compared to 5522 registrations in July the previous year.
Porsche registrations fell from 643 to 554.

Israel plays down fears of war with Syria.
Colleen Siegel
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel's outgoing peace negotiator with Syria said on Thursday that current tensions between the two countries appeared to be a storm in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinovich, who as Israel's ambassador in Washington conducted fruitless negotiations with Syria, told Israel Radio that it seemed Damascus wanted to talk rather than fight.
"It seems to me that the {(1)[MISC] Syrian priority} is still up for negotiation.
The Syrians are confused, they're definitely tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that this is essentially a storm in a teacup," he said.
Rabinovich is ending his term as ambassador.
He will be replaced by Eliahu Ben-Elissar, a former Israeli envoy in Egypt and politician from the right-wing Likud party.
Israel sent a message to Syria on Wednesday, via Washington, saying it was committed to peace and wanted to open negotiations without preconditions.
But he slammed Damascus for creating what he called a dangerous atmosphere.
Syria accused Israel on Wednesday of launching a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently tested a missile.
He said his arms purchases were for defensive purposes.

"The message we send to (Syrian President Hafez al-) Assad is that Israel is ready at any time without preconditions to enter into peace negotiations," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy told Israel Radio in an interview.
Tension has risen since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June, promising to keep the Golan Heights Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been stalled over the Golan since 1991, despite the previous government's willingness to make concessions on the Golan.
Peace talks between the two sides were last held in February.
"The voices coming out of Damascus are bad, not good.
The media...
are full of expressions and statements that should be worrying...
this artificial atmosphere is very dangerous because those who spread it can become its prisoners," Levy said.
"We expect Syria, if its face is for peace, to respond to Israel's message to enter peace negotiations, because that is our goal," he said. "
We don't want a war, God forbid.
Nobody benefits from wars. "
Israel's Channel Two television said Damascus had sent a "signal of calm" to Israel.
He gave no source for the report.
Spokesmen for Netanyahu and Levy said they could not confirm it.
The television also said Netanyahu had sent messages to reassure Syria via Cairo, the United States and Moscow.
Polish diplomat denies nurses stranded in Libya.
A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied a Polish tabloid report this week that Libya was refusing exit visas to 100 Polish nurses trying to return home after working in the North African country.
"This is not true.

To date, we are not aware of any nurses stranded or kept in Libya without their will, and we have not received any complaints, "the chargé d'affaires at the Polish embassy in Tripoli, Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, told Reuters by telephone.

Poland's Labour Ministry said this week it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but Awdankiewicz said the probe was prompted by some nurses who complained about their working conditions, such as non-payment of their wages.
He said there are about 800 Polish nurses working in Libya.
Two Iranian opposition leaders meet in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafidh
BAGHDAD 1996-08-22
An Iranian exile group based in Iraq vowed on Thursday to extend support to Iran's Kurdish rebels after they were attacked by Iranian troops deep inside Iraq last month.

A statement from Mujahideen Khalq said its leader Massoud Rajavi met in Baghdad the Secretary General of the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI) Hassan Rastegar on Wednesday and expressed his support for Iranian Kurdish rebels.
"Rajavi emphasised that the Iranian Resistance would continue to stand shoulder to shoulder with his fellow Kurds and the resistance movement in Iranian Kurdistan," he said.
A spokesman for the group said the meeting "signals a new level of cooperation between Mujahideen Khalq and Iranian Kurdish oppositions".
Iran heavily bombed targets in northern Iraq in July in pursuit of KDPI guerrillas based in Iraqi Kurdish areas outside government control in Baghdad.
Iraqi Kurdish areas bordering Iran are under the control of guerrillas from the Iraqi Kurdistan Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) group.
PUK and the Iraqi Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), Iraq's two main Kurdish factions, have had northern Iraq under their control since Iraqi forces were driven out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
Clashes between the two sides erupted over the weekend in the most serious fighting since a US-sponsored ceasefire last year.
Mujahideen Khalq said Iranian troops had also shelled KDP positions in Qasri region of Suleimaniya province near the Iranian border during the past two days.
It said about 100 Iraqi Kurds were killed or injured in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey mount air and ground attacks against targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their own Kurdish rebels.
A US-led air force in southern Turkey protects Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by Baghdad troops.
Saudi loyalty rates steady in quiet summer trade.
Saudi Arabia's interbank demand deposit rates against the dollar and the interbank demand deposit rate were mainly flat this week in quiet summer trade, the kingdom's dealers said.
"There has been no change in Saudi loyalty rates."
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays," said a dealer.
The spot riyal was placed at 3.7504 / 06 to the dollar.
One-month interbank deposits were 5-1/2, 3/8 per cent, three-month 5-5/8, 1/2 per cent and six-month 5-3/4, 5/8 per cent.
One-year funds were at six, 5-7/8 per cent.
Israel approves Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel gave Palestinian President Yasser Arafat permission on Thursday to fly over his territory to the West Bank, ending a brief Israeli-Palestinian crisis, an Arafat adviser said.
"The problem is over.
The president's aircraft has been given permission to pass through Israeli airspace, but the president is not expected to travel to the West Bank before Monday," Nabil Abu Rdainah told Reuters.

Arafat had been scheduled to meet former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in the West Bank city of Ramallah on Thursday, but the venue was changed to Gaza after Israel denied flight permission to the Palestinian leader's helicopters.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to prevent the Ramallah meeting by keeping Arafat grounded.
Arafat subsequently cancelled a meeting between Israeli and PLO officials on civil affairs at the Allenby Bridge between Jordan and the West Bank.
Abu Rdainah said Arafat had decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday, after Israel lifted the ban, because he had a busy schedule in Gaza and would only be free on Monday.
Arafat to meet Peres in Gaza after flight ban.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22

Yasser Arafat will meet Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday, after Palestinians said the right-wing Israeli government had prevented the Palestinian leader from flying to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.

Japan's Finance Minister Wataru Kubo said at a press conference on Wednesday that he believes the Bank of Japan's (BoJ) interest rate policy, which is geared towards ensuring economic growth, has not changed after the release of the central bank's "tankan" survey.
